sponseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flagella","Fimbriae","Capsule","M protein","Biofilm"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlagella\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily involved in bacterial motility. \u003Cstrong\u003EFimbriae\u003C/strong\u003E (or pili) are protein structures that can aid in bacterial attachment but do not provide significant protection. A bacterial \u003Cstrong\u003Ecapsule\u003C/strong\u003E provides some protection against phagocytosis but is not the primary mechanism of device adherence. \u003Cstrong\u003EM protein\u003C/strong\u003E is specifically found in Streptococci and is not relevant to these organisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiofilm\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as glycocalyx or extracellular slime, is produced by both \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus epidermidis\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E. This complex matrix of polysaccharides and proteins allows bacteria to:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdhere strongly to medical devices\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EForm protective barriers against antibiotics\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EResist host immune responses\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommunicate between bacterial cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Biofilm (glycocalyx/extracellular slime) produced by bacteria provides protection from antibiotics and immune responses while facilitating adherence to medical devices.","Both Staphylococcus epidermidis and Pseudomonas aeruginosa are notable biofilm-producing organisms commonly associated with device-related infections."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd.","Flemming HC. The perfect slime. Colloids Surf B Biointerfaces. 2011 Sep 1;86(2):251-9. doi: 10.1016/j.colsurfb.2011.04.025. Epub 2011 Apr 23. PMID: 21592744."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54742"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14934"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54742"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T18:12:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T18:13:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7622"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69289"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position"